{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17523914","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17523914"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:59:55+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:59:55+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13925"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13925","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13925"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.11,0.68,0.14,0.04,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6544"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49761"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6544","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6544"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13925"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"35015"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"43"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"108"},{"type":"tags","id":"128"},{"type":"tags","id":"2040"},{"type":"tags","id":"3338"},{"type":"tags","id":"3505"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"13116"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49761","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/49761"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 42-year-old man presents to his General Practice clinic with a two-week history of tingling and numbness in his hands and feet. He was diagnosed with pulmonary tuberculosis six weeks ago and commenced on standard first-line anti-tuberculosis therapy. His medical history includes type 2 diabetes mellitus, for which he takes metformin. He does not take any other regular medications and has no known allergies.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well. His vital signs are within normal limits. Neurological examination reveals reduced sensation to light touch and pinprick in a glove and stocking distribution. Proprioception and vibration sense are intact. Muscle strength and deep tendon reflexes are normal.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following medications is most likely responsible for this patient\u0027s symptoms?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Rifampicin","Isoniazid","Pyrazinamide","Ethambutol","Metformin"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient is presenting with symptoms suggestive of peripheral neuropathy, which is a known side effect of anti-tuberculosis therapy. Among the medications he is taking, \u003Cstrong\u003Eisoniazid\u003C/strong\u003E is the most likely culprit. Isoniazid-induced peripheral neuropathy is a well-documented adverse effect, occurring in up to 2-3% of patients taking standard doses, and more frequently in those with risk factors such as diabetes, alcoholism, malnutrition, or HIV infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERifampicin\u003C/strong\u003E is not commonly associated with peripheral neuropathy. Its main side effects include hepatotoxicity, gastrointestinal disturbances, and orange discoloration of body fluids.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPyrazinamide\u003C/strong\u003E can cause arthralgia and hepatotoxicity but is not typically associated with peripheral neuropathy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEthambutol\u003C/strong\u003E is known to cause optic neuritis, which can lead to color vision deficits and visual acuity changes, but it does not typically cause peripheral neuropathy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile \u003Cstrong\u003Emetformin\u003C/strong\u003E can rarely cause peripheral neuropathy, it is much less likely to be the cause compared to isoniazid, especially given the temporal relationship between the start of anti-tuberculosis therapy and the onset of symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe mechanism of isoniazid-induced peripheral neuropathy is thought to be related to pyridoxine (vitamin B6) deficiency. Isoniazid interferes with pyridoxine metabolism, which can lead to a functional deficiency. This is the reason why pyridoxine supplementation is often recommended for patients on isoniazid therapy, particularly those with risk factors for peripheral neuropathy.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Isoniazid is a common cause of peripheral neuropathy in patients on tuberculosis treatment.","Pyridoxine supplementation can help prevent isoniazid-induced peripheral neuropathy."],"references":["Prasad R, Singh A, Gupta N. Adverse drug reactions in tuberculosis and management. Indian Journal of Tuberculosis. 2019 Oct 1;66(4):520-32.","Forget EJ, Menzies D. Adverse reactions to first-line antituberculosis drugs. Expert opinion on drug safety. 2006 Mar 1;5(2):231-49."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"35015"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13925"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"35015","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/35015"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-08-03T16:38:38+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-08-03T16:38:38+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6544"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49761"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":